SIMPLE: strip
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Strip
<hw>Strip</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Stripped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Stripping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>stripen</ets>, <ets>strepen</ets>, AS. <ets>str<?/pan</ets> in
be<ets>str<?/pan</ets> to plunder; akin to D. <ets>stroopen</ets>, MHG.
<ets>stroufen</ets>, G. <ets>streifen</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
deprive; to bereave; to make destitute; to plunder; especially, to
deprive of a covering; to skin; to peel; <as>as, to <ex>strip</ex> a man
of his possession, his rights, his privileges, his reputation; to
<ex>strip</ex> one of his clothes; to <ex>strip</ex> a beast of his
skin; to <ex>strip</ex> a tree of its bark.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And <qex>strippen</qex> her out of her rude array.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>stripped</qex> Joseph out of his coat.</q> <rj><qau>Gen.
xxxvii. 23.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Opinions which . . . no clergyman could have avowed without
imminent risk of being <qex>stripped</qex> of his gown.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To divest of clothing; to uncover.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Before the folk herself <qex>strippeth</qex> she.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Strip</qex> your sword stark naked.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To dismantle; <as>as, to
<ex>strip</ex> a ship of rigging, spars, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Agric.)</fld> <def>To pare off the surface of, as
land, in strips.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To deprive of all milk; to milk dry; to draw the
last milk from; hence, to milk with a peculiar movement of the hand on
the teats at the last of a milking; <as>as, to <ex>strip</ex> a
cow</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To pass; to get clear of; to outstrip.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When first they <qex>stripped</qex> the Malean promontory.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Before he reached it he was out of breath,⟦br⟧
And then the other <qex>stripped</qex> him.</q> <rj><qau>Beau. &
Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To pull or tear off, as a covering; to remove; to
wrest away; <as>as, to <ex>strip</ex> the skin from a beast; to
<ex>strip</ex> the bark from a tree; to <ex>strip</ex> the clothes from
a man's back; to <ex>strip</ex> away all disguises.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>strip</qex> bad habits from a corrupted heart, is
<qex>stripping</qex> off the skin.</q> <rj><qau>Gilpin.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To tear off (the
thread) from a bolt or nut; <as>as, the thread is
<ex>stripped</ex></as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>To tear off the thread
from (a bolt or nut); <as>as, the bolt is
<ex>stripped</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To remove the metal coating from (a plated article),
as by acids or electrolytic action.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Carding)</fld> <def>To remove fiber, flock, or
lint from; -- said of the teeth of a card when it becomes partly
clogged.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>To pick the cured leaves from the stalks of
(tobacco) and tie them into ⟦ldquo⟧hands⟦rdquo⟧; to remove the midrib
from (tobacco leaves).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- strip mine. A mine in which the unwanted layers (called the
overburdewn) above the desirable ore is stripped, i.e. removed by
excavation, leaving a pit in which the ore is exposed; in contrast with
mines in which the ore is accessed and removed through a shaft or
tunnel, without removing the layers of earth above it. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- striptease, an act in which a performer (usu. female) removes her
clothing piece by piece; -- often performed to musical accompaniment. It
was popular in burlesque theaters. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1427 --></p>

<p><ent>Strip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Strip
<hw>Strip</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To take
off, or become divested of, clothes or covering; to undress.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>To fail in the thread; to lose
the thread, as a bolt, screw, or nut. See <er>Strip</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>, 8.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Strip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Strip
<hw>Strip</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A narrow piece, or one
comparatively long; <as>as, a <ex>strip</ex> of cloth; a <ex>strip</ex>
of land.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>A trough for washing
ore.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Gunnery)</fld> <def>The issuing of a projectile
from a rifled gun without acquiring the spiral motion.</def>
<rj><au>Farrow.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stripe</ent>⟦br⟧
